# Scoring system

Ten signals, each normalized to [0, 1], combined with configurable weights.

## Math-derived signals (no LLM)

| Signal | Weight | Source |
|--------|--------|--------|
| Surprise | 0.12 | Gap between prevailing odds and actual resolution |
| Narrative arc | 0.08 | Volatility, reversals, max swing in price history |
| Volume | 0.05 | Sigmoid-capped so mega-markets don't dominate |

## LLM-derived signals (7 dimensions, batched)

| Signal | Weight | What it measures |
|--------|--------|------------------|
| Shareability | 0.20 | Would someone send this to a friend unprompted? |
| Humor | 0.15 | Genuinely funny, not just surprising |
| Absurdity | 0.10 | "Wait, people actually bet on that?" |
| Relatability | 0.10 | Broad audience appeal vs niche |
| Controversy | 0.08 | Sparks debate or strong opinions |
| WTF factor | 0.07 | Pure "I can't believe this exists" energy |
| Significance | 0.05 | Relates to major real-world events |

## Domain classification

Each market is classified into one of 5 domains by the LLM during scoring:
- Politics, Pop Culture, Sports, Tech/Business, Wildcard

All 7 LLM dimensions are scored RELATIVE TO the domain. A 7/10 humor in Politics means funny for a political market; a 6/10 controversy in Politics means only moderately divisive for politics (where everything is already somewhat controversial). Domain is stored in `scores.domain`.

LLM scoring uses Haiku 4.5 with batches of 6 markets per API call. The prompt sends question, resolution, and volume for each market. Response includes domain + 7 dimension scores per market. Falls back to keyword heuristics (including keyword-based domain guess) on batch failure.

Volume uses a sigmoid centered on the dataset median — $100K and $1B are NOT 10,000x apart in score.
